[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The **density matrix renormalization group** (**DMRG**) is a numerical variational technique devised to obtain the low-energy physics of quantum many-body systems with high accuracy.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The DMRG algorithm attempts to find the lowest-energy matrix product state wavefunction of a Hamiltonian.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] White and it is nowadays the most efficient method for 1-dimensional systems.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The first application of the DMRG, by Steven R.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] White and Reinhard Noack, was to find the spectrum of a 1D tight-binding model, which is the discrete lattice version of a 1D particle in a box; this model had been proposed by Kenneth G.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Wilson as a test for any new renormalization group method, because they all happened to fail with this simple problem.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] After succeeding with the *toy model*, the DMRG method was tried with success on the quantum Heisenberg model.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The main problem of quantum many-body physics is the fact that the Hilbert space grows exponentially with size.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] In other words if one considers a lattice, with some Hilbert space of dimension d on each site of the lattice, then the total Hilbert space would have dimension $d^{N}$ , where N is the number of sites on the lattice.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] For example, a spin-1/2 chain of length *L* has 2*L* degrees of freedom.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The DMRG is an iterative, variational method that reduces effective degrees of freedom to those most important for a target state.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The state one is most often interested in is the ground state.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] After a warmup cycle, the method splits the system into two subsystems, or blocks, which need not have equal sizes, and two sites in between.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] A set of *representative states* has been chosen for the block during the warmup.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] This set of left blocks + two sites + right blocks is known as the **superblock**.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Now a candidate for the ground state of the superblock, which is a reduced version of the full system, may be found.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] It may have a rather poor accuracy, but the method is iterative and improves with the steps below.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The candidate ground state that has been found is projected into the Hilbert subspace for each block using a density matrix, hence the name.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Thus, the *relevant states* for each block are updated.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Now one of the blocks grows at the expense of the other and the procedure is repeated.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] When the growing block reaches maximum size, the other starts to grow in its place.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Each time we return to the original (equal sizes) situation, we say that a *sweep* has been completed.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Normally, a few sweeps are enough to get a precision of a part in 1010 for a 1D lattice.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] A practical implementation of the DMRG algorithm is a lengthy work.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] It has been also extended to work on tree graphs, and has found applications in the study of dendrimers.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] For 2D systems with one of the dimensions much larger than the other DMRG is also accurate, and has proved useful in the study of ladders.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The method has been extended to study equilibrium statistical physics in 2D, and to analyze non-equilibrium phenomena in 1D.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The DMRG has also been applied to the field of quantum chemistry to study strongly correlated systems.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Let us consider an "infinite" DMRG algorithm for the $S=1$ antiferromagnetic quantum Heisenberg chain.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The recipe can be applied for every translationally invariant one-dimensional lattice.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] DMRG is a renormalization-group technique because it offers an efficient truncation of the Hilbert space of one-dimensional quantum systems.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] To simulate an infinite chain, start with four sites.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The first is the *block site*, the last the *universe-block site* and the remaining are the *added sites*, the right one is added to the universe-block site and the other to the block site.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] With this base the spin operators are $S_{x}$ , $S_{y}$ and $S_{z}$ for the single site.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] At the starting point all four Hilbert spaces are equivalent to ${\mathfrak {H}}$ , all spin operators are equivalent to $S_{x}$ , $S_{y}$ and $S_{z}$ and $H_{B}=H_{U}=0$ .
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] In the following iterations, this is only true for the left and right sites.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The ingredients are the four block operators and the four universe-block operators, which at the first iteration are $3\times 3$ matrices, the three left-site spin operators and the three right-site spin operators, which are always $3\times 3$ matrices.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The Hamiltonian matrix of the *superblock* (the chain), which at the first iteration has only four sites, is formed by these operators.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] These operators live in the superblock state space: ${\mathfrak {H}}_{SB}={\mathfrak {H}}_{B}\otimes {\mathfrak {H}}_{l}\otimes {\mathfrak {H}}_{r}\otimes {\mathfrak {H}}_{U}$ , the base is $\{|f\rangle =|u\rangle \otimes |t\rangle \otimes |s\rangle \otimes |r\rangle \}$ .
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] At this point you must choose the eigenstate of the Hamiltonian for which some observables is calculated, this is the *target state* .
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] This step is the most time-consuming part of the algorithm.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] If $|\Psi \rangle =\sum \Psi _{i,j,k,w}|u_{i},t_{j},s_{k},r_{w}\rangle$ is the target state, expectation value of various operators can be measured at this point using $|\Psi \rangle$ .
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Form the reduced density matrix $\rho$ for the first two block system, the block and the left-site.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Diagonalize $\rho$ and form the $m\times (d*3)$ matrix T , which rows are the m eigenvectors associated with the m largest eigenvalues $e_{\alpha }$ of $\rho$ .
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] So T is formed by the most significant eigenstates of the reduced density matrix.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The algorithm stops successfully when the observable converges to some value.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The success of the DMRG for 1D systems is related to the fact that it is a variational method within the space of matrix product states (MPS).
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] where $s_{1}\cdots s_{N}$ are the values of the e.g.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] *z*-component of the spin in a spin chain, and the *A**s**i* are matrices of arbitrary dimension *m*.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] As *m* → ∞, the representation becomes exact.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] In quantum chemistry, $A^{s_{1}}$ (for a given $s_{i}$ ) and $A^{s_{N}}$ (for a given $s_{N}$ ) are traditionally chosen to be row and column matrices, respectively.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] This way, the result of $A^{s_{1}}\ldots A^{s_{N}}$ is a scalar value and the trace operation is unnecessary.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] N is the number of sites (the orbitals basically) used in the simulation.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Such gauge freedom is employed to transform the matrices into a canonical form.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] for all i , and (3) mixed-canonical form when both left- and right-normalized matrices exist among the N matrices in the above MPS *ansatz*.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The goal of the DMRG calculation is then to solve for the elements of each of the $A^{s_{i}}$ matrices.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The so-called one-site and two-site algorithms have been devised for this purpose.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] In the one-site algorithm, only one matrix (one site) whose elements are solved for at a time.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Two-site just means that two matrices are first contracted (multiplied) into a single matrix, and then its elements are solved.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The two-site algorithm is proposed because the one-site algorithm is much more prone to getting trapped at a local minimum.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Having the MPS in one of the above canonical forms has the advantage of making the computation more favorable - it leads to the ordinary eigenvalue problem.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Without canonicalization, one will be dealing with a generalized eigenvalue problem.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] In 2004, the time-evolving block decimation method was developed to implement real-time evolution of matrix product states.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] The idea is based on the classical simulation of a quantum computer.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] Subsequently, a new method was devised to compute real-time evolution within the DMRG formalism based on Runge-Kutta.
[src:tensor-networks/density-matrix-renormalization-group] In recent years, some proposals extending the definition of the matrix product states and DMRG methods to 2D and 3D have been put forward.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] A **matrix product state (MPS)** is a representation of a quantum many-body state.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] It is at the core of the density matrix renormalization group (DMRG) algorithm.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Here $A_{i}^{(s_{i})}$ are the $D_{i}\times D_{i+1}$ matrices ( D is the dimension of the virtual subsystems) and $|s_{i}\rangle$ are the single-site basis states.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] For periodic boundary conditions, we consider $D_{N+1}=D_{1}$ , and for open boundary conditions $D_{1}=1$ .
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] The parameter D is related to the entanglement between particles.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] In particular, if the state is a product state (i.e. not entangled at all), it can be described as a matrix product state with $D=1$ . $\{s_{i}\}$ represents a d -dimensional local space on site $i=1,2,...,N$ .
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] For states that are translationally symmetric, we can choose: $A_{1}^{(s)}=A_{2}^{(s)}=\cdots =A_{N}^{(s)}\equiv A^{(s)}.$ In general, every state can be written in the MPS form (with D growing exponentially with the particle number *N*).
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Note that the MPS decomposition is not unique.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] MPS are practical when D is small – for example, does not depend on the particle number.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Except for a small number of specific cases (some mentioned in the section Examples), such a thing is not possible, though in many cases it serves as a good approximation.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] For emphasis placed on the graphical reasoning of tensor networks, see the introduction.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] For example, the wave function of the system described by the Heisenberg model is defined by the $2^{N}$ dimensional tensor, whereas for the Hubbard model the rank is $4^{N}$ .
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] The main idea of the MPS approach is to separate physical degrees of freedom of each site, so that the wave function can be rewritten as the product of N matrices, where each matrix corresponds to one particular site.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] The whole procedure includes the series of reshaping and singular value decompositions (SVD).
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] There are three ways to represent wave function as an MPS: left-canonical decomposition, right-canonical decomposition, and mixed-canonical decomposition.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] The decomposition of the $d^{N}$ -dimensional tensor starts with the separation of the very left index, i.e., the first index $s_{1}$ , which describes physical degrees of freedom of the first site.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] In the relation above, matrices D and $V^{\dagger }$ are multiplied and form the matrix $\psi _{\alpha _{1},(s_{2}...s_{N})}$ and $r_{1}\leq d$ . $A_{\alpha _{1}}^{s_{1}}$ stores the information about the first lattice site.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] However, due to the exponential growth of the matrix dimensions in most of the cases it is impossible to perform the exact decomposition.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Note that each matrix U in the SVD is a semi-unitary matrix with property $U^{\dagger }U=I$ .
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Since matrices are left-normalized, we call the composition left-canonical.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Similarly, the decomposition can be started from the very right site.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Since each matrix V in the SVD is a semi-unitary matrix with property $V^{\dagger }V=I$ , the B -matrices are right-normalized and obey $\sum _{s_{i}}B^{s_{i}}B^{s_{i}\dagger }=I$ .
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Hence, the decomposition is called right-canonical.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] The decomposition performs from both the right and from the left.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] This notation uses matrices with entries being state vectors (instead of complex numbers), and when multiplying matrices using tensor product for its entries (instead of product of two complex numbers).
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Note that tensor product is not commutative.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] W state, i.e., the superposition of all the computational basis states of Hamming weight one.
[src:tensor-networks/matrix-product-state] Even though the state is permutation-symmetric, its simplest MPS representation is not.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] In mathematics and physics, **Penrose graphical notation** or **tensor diagram notation** is a (usually handwritten) visual depiction of multilinear functions or tensors proposed by Roger Penrose in 1971.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] A diagram in the notation consists of several shapes linked together by lines.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The notation widely appears in modern quantum theory, particularly in matrix product states and quantum circuits.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] In particular, categorical quantum mechanics (which includes ZX-calculus) is a fully comprehensive reformulation of quantum theory in terms of Penrose diagrams.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The notation has been studied extensively by Predrag Cvitanović, who used it, along with Feynman's diagrams and other related notations in developing "birdtracks", a group-theoretical diagram to classify the classical Lie groups.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] Penrose's notation has also been generalized using representation theory to spin networks in physics, and with the presence of matrix groups to trace diagrams in linear algebra.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] In the language of multilinear algebra, each shape represents a multilinear function.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The lines attached to shapes represent the inputs or outputs of a function, and attaching shapes together in some way is essentially the composition of functions.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] In the language of tensor algebra, a particular tensor is associated with a particular shape with many lines projecting upwards and downwards, corresponding to abstract upper and lower indices of tensors respectively.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] Connecting lines between two shapes corresponds to contraction of indices.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] One advantage of this notation is that one does not have to invent new letters for new indices.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] This notation is also explicitly basis-independent.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] Each shape represents a matrix, and tensor multiplication is done horizontally, and matrix multiplication is done vertically.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The metric tensor is represented by a U-shaped loop or an upside-down U-shaped loop, depending on the type of tensor that is used.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The Levi-Civita antisymmetric tensor is represented by a thick horizontal bar with sticks pointing downwards or upwards, depending on the type of tensor that is used.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The structure constants ( ${\gamma _{ab}}^{c}$ ) of a Lie algebra are represented by a small triangle with one line pointing upwards and two lines pointing downwards.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] Contraction of indices is represented by joining the index lines together.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] Symmetrization of indices is represented by a thick zigzag or wavy bar crossing the index lines horizontally.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] Antisymmetrization of indices is represented by a thick straight line crossing the index lines horizontally.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The determinant is formed by applying antisymmetrization to the indices.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The covariant derivative ( $\nabla$ ) is represented by a circle around the tensor(s) to be differentiated and a line joined from the circle pointing downwards to represent the lower index of the derivative.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The diagrammatic notation is useful in manipulating tensor algebra.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] It usually involves a few simple "identities" of tensor manipulations.
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] For example, $\varepsilon _{a...c}\varepsilon ^{a...c}=n!$ , where *n* is the number of dimensions, is a common "identity".
[src:tensor-networks/penrose-graphical-notation] The notation has been extended with support for spinors and twistors.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] In quantum information theory, a **quantum circuit** is a model for quantum computation, similar to classical circuits, in which a computation is a sequence of quantum gates, measurements, initializations of qubits to known values, and possibly other actions.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The minimum set of actions that a circuit needs to be able to perform on the qubits to enable quantum computation is known as DiVincenzo's criteria.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Circuits are written such that the horizontal axis is time, starting at the left hand side and ending at the right.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Horizontal lines are qubits, doubled lines represent classical bits.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The items that are connected by these lines are operations performed on the qubits, such as measurements or gates.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] These lines define the sequence of events, and are usually not physical cables.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The graphical depiction of quantum circuit elements is described using a variant of the Penrose graphical notation.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Richard Feynman used an early version of the quantum circuit notation in 1986.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Most elementary logic gates of a classical computer are not reversible.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Thus, for instance, for an AND gate one cannot always recover the two input bits from the output bit; for example, if the output bit is 0, we cannot tell from this whether the input bits are 01 or 10 or 00.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] However, reversible gates in classical computers are easily constructed for bit strings of any length; moreover, these are actually of practical interest, since irreversible gates must always increase physical entropy.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] A reversible gate is a reversible function on *n*-bit data that returns *n*-bit data, where an *n*-bit data is a string of bits *x*1,*x*2, ...,*x**n* of length *n*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The set of *n*-bit data is the space {0,1}*n*, which consists of 2*n* strings of 0's and 1's.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] More precisely: an *n*-bit reversible gate is a bijective mapping *f* from the set {0,1}*n* of *n*-bit data onto itself.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] An example of such a reversible gate *f* is a mapping that applies a fixed permutation to its inputs.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] For reasons of practical engineering, one typically studies gates only for small values of *n*, e.g.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] These gates can be easily described by tables.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The quantum logic gates are reversible unitary transformations on at least one qubit.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Multiple qubits taken together are referred to as quantum registers.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] To define quantum gates, we first need to specify the quantum replacement of an *n*-bit datum.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] This is by definition the space of complex-valued functions on {0,1}*n* and is naturally an inner product space. $\ell ^{2}$ means the function is a square-integrable function.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] This space can also be regarded as consisting of linear combinations, or superpositions, of classical bit strings.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Note that *H*QB(*n*) is a vector space over the complex numbers of dimension 2*n*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The elements of this vector space are the possible state-vectors of *n*-qubit quantum registers.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] is a special *n*-qubit register corresponding to the function which maps this classical bit string to 1 and maps all other bit strings to 0; these 2*n* special *n*-qubit registers are called *computational basis states*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] All *n*-qubit registers are complex linear combinations of these computational basis states.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Quantum logic gates, in contrast to classical logic gates, are always reversible.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] One requires a special kind of reversible function, namely a unitary mapping, that is, a linear transformation of a complex inner product space that preserves the Hermitian inner product.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] An *n*-qubit (reversible) quantum gate is a unitary mapping *U* from the space *H*QB(*n*) of *n*-qubit registers onto itself.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Typically, we are only interested in gates for small values of *n*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Note that *W**f* permutes the computational basis states.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Of particular importance is the controlled NOT gate (also called CNOT gate) *W*CNOT defined on a quantized 2 qubit.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Other examples of quantum logic gates derived from classical ones are the Toffoli gate and the Fredkin gate.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] However, the Hilbert-space structure of the qubits permits many quantum gates that are not induced by classical ones.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Again, we consider first *reversible* classical computation.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Conceptually, there is no difference between a reversible *n*-bit circuit and a reversible *n*-bit logic gate: either one is just an invertible function on the space of *n* bit data.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] However, as mentioned in the previous section, for engineering reasons we would like to have a small number of simple reversible gates, that can be put together to assemble any reversible circuit.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] To explain this assembly process, suppose we have a reversible *n*-bit gate *f* and a reversible *m*-bit gate *g*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Putting them together means producing a new circuit by connecting some set of *k* outputs of *f* to some set of *k* inputs of *g* as in the figure below.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The resulting circuit is also reversible and operates on *n*+*m*−*k* bits.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] We will refer to this scheme as a *classical assemblage* (This concept corresponds to a technical definition in Kitaev's pioneering paper cited below).
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] In composing these reversible machines, it is important to ensure that the intermediate machines are also reversible.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] This condition assures that *intermediate* "garbage" is not created (the net physical effect would be to increase entropy, which is one of the motivations for going through this exercise).
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Note that each horizontal line on the above picture represents either 0 or 1, not these probabilities.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Since quantum computations are reversible, at each 'step' the number of lines must be the same number of input lines.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Also, each input combination must be mapped to a single combination at each 'step'.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] This means that each intermediate combination in a quantum circuit is a bijective function of the input.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Now it is possible to show that the Toffoli gate is a universal gate.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Notice that the result always has a string of *m* zeros as the ancilla bits.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] No "rubbish" is ever produced, and so this computation is indeed one that, in a physical sense, generates no entropy.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] This issue is carefully discussed in Kitaev's article.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] More generally, any function *f* (bijective or not) can be simulated by a circuit of Toffoli gates.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Obviously, if the mapping fails to be injective, at some point in the simulation (for example as the last step) some "garbage" has to be produced.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] For quantum circuits a similar composition of qubit gates can be defined.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] That is, associated to any *classical assemblage* as above, we can produce a reversible quantum circuit when in place of *f* we have an *n*-qubit gate *U* and in place of *g* we have an *m*-qubit gate *W*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The fact that connecting gates this way gives rise to a unitary mapping on *n*+*m*−*k* qubit space is easy to check.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] In a real quantum computer the physical connection between the gates is a major engineering challenge, since it is one of the places where decoherence may occur.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] There are also universality theorems for certain sets of well-known gates; such a universality theorem exists, for instance, for the pair consisting of the single qubit phase gate *U*θ mentioned above (for a suitable value of θ), together with the 2-qubit CNOT gate *W*CNOT.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] However, the universality theorem for the quantum case is somewhat weaker than the one for the classical case; it asserts only that any reversible *n*-qubit circuit can be *approximated* arbitrarily well by circuits assembled from these two elementary gates.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Note that there are uncountably many possible single qubit phase gates, one for every possible angle θ, so they cannot all be represented by a finite circuit constructed from {*U*θ, *W*CNOT}.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] So far we have not shown how quantum circuits are used to perform computations.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Since many important numerical problems reduce to computing a unitary transformation *U* on a finite-dimensional space (the celebrated discrete Fourier transform being a prime example), one might expect that some quantum circuit could be designed to carry out the transformation *U*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] In principle, one needs only to prepare an *n* qubit state ψ as an appropriate superposition of computational basis states for the input and measure the output *U*ψ.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] This does not prevent quantum circuits for the discrete Fourier transform from being used as intermediate steps in other quantum circuits, but the use is more subtle.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] In fact quantum computations are *probabilistic*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] We now provide a mathematical model for how quantum circuits can simulate *probabilistic* but classical computations.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Consider an *r*-qubit circuit *U* with register space *H*QB(*r*).
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] The contents *x* = *x*1, ..., *x**m* of the classical input register are used to initialize the qubit register in some way.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] where there are *r*-*m* underbraced zeroed inputs.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Nevertheless, this perfect initialization is completely unrealistic.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Let us assume therefore that the initialization is a mixed state given by some density operator *S* which is near the idealized input in some appropriate metric, e.g.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Similarly, the output register space is related to the qubit register, by a *Y* valued observable *A*.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Note that observables in quantum mechanics are usually defined in terms of *projection valued measures* on **R**; if the variable happens to be discrete, the projection valued measure reduces to a family {Eλ} indexed on some parameter λ ranging over a countable set.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] on *Y* can be used to determine *F*(*x*) with an arbitrarily small probability of error by majority sampling, for a sufficiently large sample size.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] Specifically, take *k* independent samples from the probability distribution Pr on *Y* and choose a value on which more than half of the samples agree.
[src:tensor-networks/quantum-circuit] This follows by applying the Chernoff bound.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] In multilinear algebra, a **tensor contraction** is an operation on a tensor that arises from the canonical pairing of a vector space and its dual.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] When calculating with matrices or tensors, often it's useful to move the second tensor up, and put the result underneath, just for calculation purposes.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] That way, each row of the first matrix (1234), and each column of the second matrix (5678), point to the cell of the result that they produce.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Of course, these matrices can be larger than 2x2; often 3x3 or 4x4 are used, but any size is allowed.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] In simple index notation, this is written ${\textstyle \sum _{j=1}^{2}a_{ij}\times b_{jk}=c_{ik}}$ where i, j and k all range over 1, 2.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Notice how the index j, in between, disappears; this is the essence of tensor contraction.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] The superscripts work just like subscripts, with a different meaning.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Only repeated, raised and lowered indices are summed over.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Objects can have more than two indices, also.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Tensor contraction can be seen as a generalization of the trace.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Let *V* be a vector space over a field *k*.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] The core of the contraction operation, and the simplest case, is the canonical pairing of *V* with its dual vector space *V*∗.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] The map *C* defines the contraction operation on a tensor of type (1, 1), which is an element of $V\otimes V^{*}$ .
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Note that the result is a scalar (an element of *k*).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] In finite dimensions, using the natural isomorphism between $V\otimes V^{*}$ and the space of linear maps from *V* to *V*, one obtains a basis-free definition of the trace.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] (where there are *m* factors *V* and *n* factors *V*∗).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Applying the canonical pairing to the *k*th *V* factor and the *l*th *V*∗ factor, and using the identity on all other factors, defines the (*k*, *l*) contraction operation, which is a linear map that yields a tensor of type (*m* − 1, *n* − 1).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] By analogy with the (1, 1) case, the general contraction operation is sometimes called the trace.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] (where *v**i* are the components of *v* in a particular basis and *f**i* are the components of *f* in the corresponding dual basis).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] A general contraction is denoted by labeling one covariant index and one contravariant index with the same letter, summation over that index being implied by the summation convention.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] The resulting contracted tensor inherits the remaining indices of the original tensor.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] As in the previous example, contraction on a pair of indices that are either both contravariant or both covariant is not possible in general.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] However, in the presence of an inner product (also known as a metric) *g*, such contractions are possible.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] One uses the metric to raise or lower one of the indices, as needed, and then one uses the usual operation of contraction.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] The combined operation is known as *metric contraction*.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Contraction is often applied to tensor fields over spaces (e.g.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Euclidean space, manifolds, or schemes).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Since the role of *x* is not complicated here, it is often suppressed, and the notation for tensor fields becomes identical to that for purely algebraic tensors.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Over a Riemannian manifold, a metric (field of inner products) is available, and both metric and non-metric contractions are crucial to the theory.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] For example, the Ricci tensor is a non-metric contraction of the Riemann curvature tensor, and the scalar curvature is the unique metric contraction of the Ricci tensor.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] One can also view contraction of a tensor field in the context of modules over an appropriate ring of functions on the manifold or the context of sheaves of modules over the structure sheaf; see the discussion at the end of this article.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] As an application of the contraction of a tensor field, let *V* be a vector field on a Riemannian manifold (for example, Euclidean space).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Let $V^{\alpha }{}_{\beta }$ be the covariant derivative of *V* (in some choice of coordinates).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] In general, one can define various divergence operations on higher-rank tensor fields, as follows.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] If *T* is a tensor field with at least one contravariant index, taking the covariant differential and contracting the chosen contravariant index with the new covariant index corresponding to the differential results in a new tensor of rank one lower than that of *T*.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] One can generalize the core contraction operation (vector with dual vector) in a slightly different way, by considering a pair of tensors *T* and *U*.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] The tensor product $T\otimes U$ is a new tensor, which, if it has at least one covariant and one contravariant index, can be contracted.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] The case where *T* is a vector and *U* is a dual vector is exactly the core operation introduced first in this article.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] In tensor index notation, to contract two tensors with each other, one places them side by side (juxtaposed) as factors of the same term.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] This implements the tensor product, yielding a composite tensor.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Contracting two indices in this composite tensor implements the desired contraction of the two tensors.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] For example, matrices can be represented as tensors of type (1,1) with the first index being contravariant and the second index being covariant.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Let $\Lambda ^{\alpha }{}_{\beta }$ be the components of one matrix and let $\mathrm {M} ^{\beta }{}_{\gamma }$ be the components of a second matrix.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Also, the interior product of a vector with a differential form is a special case of the contraction of two tensors with each other.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Let *R* be a commutative ring and let *M* be a finite free module over *R*.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Then contraction operates on the full (mixed) tensor algebra of *M* in exactly the same way as it does in the case of vector spaces over a field.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] More generally, let *O*X be a sheaf of commutative rings over a topological space *X*, e.g.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] *O*X could be the structure sheaf of a complex manifold, analytic space, or scheme.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Let *M* be a locally free sheaf of modules over *O*X of finite rank.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-contraction] Then the dual of *M* is still well-behaved and contraction operations make sense in this context.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] The wave function is encoded as a tensor contraction of a network of individual tensors.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] The structure of the individual tensors can impose global symmetries on the wave function (such as antisymmetry under exchange of fermions) or restrict the wave function to specific quantum numbers, like total charge, angular momentum, or spin.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] It is also possible to derive strict bounds on quantities like entanglement and correlation length using the mathematical structure of the tensor network.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] This has made tensor networks useful in theoretical studies of quantum information in many-body systems.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] They have also proved useful in variational studies of ground states, excited states, and dynamics of strongly correlated many-body systems.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In general, a tensor network diagram (Penrose diagram) can be viewed as a graph where nodes (or vertices) represent individual tensors, while edges represent summation over an index.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] Free indices are depicted as edges (or *legs*) attached to a single vertex only.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] Sometimes, there is also additional meaning to a node's shape.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] For instance, one can use trapezoids for unitary matrices or tensors with similar behaviour.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] This way, flipped trapezoids would be interpreted as complex conjugates to them.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] Foundational research on tensor networks began in 1971 with a paper by Roger Penrose.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In "Applications of negative dimensional tensors" Penrose developed tensor diagram notation, describing how the diagrammatic language of tensor networks could be used in applications in physics.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] White developed the density matrix renormalization group (DMRG) for quantum lattice systems.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] The DMRG was the first successful tensor network and associated algorithm.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In 2002, Guifré Vidal and Reinhard Werner attempted to quantify entanglement, laying the groundwork for quantum resource theories.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] This was also the first description of the use of tensor networks as mathematical tools for describing quantum systems.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In 2004, Frank Verstraete and Ignacio Cirac developed the theory of matrix product states, projected entangled pair states, and variational renormalization group methods for quantum spin systems.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In 2006, Vidal developed the multi-scale entanglement renormalization ansatz (MERA).
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In 2007 he developed entanglement renormalization for quantum lattice systems.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In 2010, Ulrich Schollwock developed the density-matrix renormalization group for the simulation of one-dimensional strongly correlated quantum lattice systems.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In 2014, Román Orús introduced tensor networks for complex quantum systems and machine learning, as well as tensor network theories of symmetries, fermions, entanglement and holography.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] Tensor networks have been adapted for supervised learning, taking advantage of similar mathematical structure in variational studies in quantum mechanics and large-scale machine learning.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] This crossover has spurred collaboration between researchers in artificial intelligence and quantum information science.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] In June 2019, Google, the Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics, and X (company), released TensorNetwork, an open-source library for efficient tensor calculations.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] The main interest in tensor networks and their study from the perspective of machine learning is to reduce the number of trainable parameters (in a layer) by approximating a high-order tensor with a network of lower-order ones.
[src:tensor-networks/tensor-network] Using the so-called tensor train technique (TT), one can reduce an N-order tensor (containing exponentially many trainable parameters) to a chain of N tensors of order 2 or 3, which gives us a polynomial number of parameters.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] In linear algebra, the **trace** of a square matrix **A**, denoted tr(**A**), is defined as a sum of the elements on its main diagonal, $a_{11}+a_{22}+\dots +a_{nn}$ .
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] It is only defined for a square matrix (*n* × *n*).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] It can be shown that the trace of a matrix is equal to the sum of its eigenvalues (counted with algebraic multiplicities), see below.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Thus, similar matrices have the same trace.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] As a consequence, one can define the trace of a linear operator mapping a finite-dimensional vector space into itself, since all matrices describing such an operator with respect to a basis are similar.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace is related to the derivative of the determinant (see Jacobi's formula).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The **trace** of an *n* × *n* square matrix **A** is defined as $\operatorname {tr} (\mathbf {A} )=\sum _{i=1}^{n}a_{ii}=a_{11}+a_{22}+\dots +a_{nn}$ where *aii* denotes the entry on the i th row and i th column of **A**.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The entries of **A** can be real numbers, complex numbers, or more generally elements of a field F.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace is not defined for non-square matrices.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] That is, ${\begin{aligned}\operatorname {tr} (\mathbf {A} +\mathbf {B} )&=\operatorname {tr} (\mathbf {A} )+\operatorname {tr} (\mathbf {B} )\\\operatorname {tr} (c\mathbf {A} )&=c\operatorname {tr} (\mathbf {A} )\end{aligned}}$ for all square matrices **A** and **B**, and all scalars c.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] This follows immediately from the fact that transposing a square matrix does not affect elements along the main diagonal.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace of a square matrix which is the product of two matrices can be rewritten as the sum of entry-wise products of their elements, i.e. as the sum of all elements of their Hadamard product.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] If one views any real *m* × *n* matrix as a vector of length mn (an operation called vectorization) then the above operation on **A** and **B** coincides with the standard dot product.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] According to the above expression, tr(**A**⊤**A**) is a sum of squares and hence is nonnegative, equal to zero if and only if **A** is zero.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] These demonstrate the positive-definiteness and symmetry required of an inner product; it is common to call tr(**A**⊤**B**) the Frobenius inner product of **A** and **B**.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] This is a natural inner product on the vector space of all real matrices of fixed dimensions.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The Frobenius inner product and norm arise frequently in matrix calculus and statistics.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The Frobenius inner product may be extended to a hermitian inner product on the complex vector space of all complex matrices of a fixed size, by replacing **B** by its complex conjugate.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The symmetry of the Frobenius inner product may be phrased more directly as follows: the matrices in the trace of a product can be switched without changing the result.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] This is notable both for the fact that **AB** does not usually equal **BA**, and also since the trace of either does not usually equal tr(**A**)tr(**B**).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The similarity-invariance of the trace, meaning that tr(**A**) = tr(**P**−1**AP**) for any square matrix **A** and any invertible matrix **P** of the same dimensions, is a fundamental consequence.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Note that this is not true in general for more than three factors.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] For $n\times n$ matrices, imposing the normalization $f(\mathbf {I} )=n$ makes f equal to the trace.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] where *λ*1, ..., *λ**n* are the eigenvalues of **A** counted with algebraic multiplicity.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] This holds true even if **A** is a real matrix and some (or all) of the eigenvalues are complex numbers, or more generally over any field with eigenvalues taken in an algebraic closure.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The identity follows from the fact that **A** is always similar to its Jordan form, an upper triangular matrix having *λ*1, ..., *λn* on the main diagonal, together with the similarity-invariance of the trace discussed above.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] One can state this as "the trace is a map of Lie algebras gl*n* → *k* from operators to scalars", as the commutator of scalars is trivial (it is an Abelian Lie algebra).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] In particular, using similarity invariance, it follows that the identity matrix is never similar to the commutator of any pair of matrices.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Conversely, any square matrix with zero trace is a linear combination of the commutators of pairs of matrices.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Moreover, any square matrix with zero trace is unitarily equivalent to a square matrix with diagonal consisting of all zeros.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace of an $n\times n$ matrix A is the coefficient of $t^{n-1}$ in the characteristic polynomial, possibly changed of sign, according to the convention in the definition of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Precisely this means that the trace is the derivative of the determinant function at the identity matrix.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] is more general and describes the differential of the determinant at an arbitrary square matrix, in terms of the trace and the adjugate of the matrix.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] A related characterization of the trace applies to linear vector fields.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The components of this vector field are linear functions (given by the rows of **A**).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Its divergence div **F** is a constant function, whose value is equal to tr(**A**).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] By the divergence theorem, one can interpret this in terms of flows: if **F**(**x**) represents the velocity of a fluid at location **x** and U is a region in **R***n*, the net flow of the fluid out of U is given by tr(**A**) · vol(*U*), where vol(*U*) is the volume of U.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The result will not depend on the basis chosen, since different bases will give rise to similar matrices, allowing for the possibility of a basis-independent definition for the trace of a linear map.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Such a definition can be given using the canonical isomorphism between the space of linear endomorphisms of V of finite rank and *V* ⊗ *V**, where *V** is the dual space of V.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Then the trace of the decomposable element *v* ⊗ *g* is defined to be *g*(*v*); the trace of a general element is defined by linearity.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace of a linear map *f* : *V* → *V* of finite rank can then be defined as the trace, in the above sense, of the element of *V* ⊗ *V** corresponding to *f* under the above-mentioned canonical isomorphism.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Using an explicit basis for V and the corresponding dual basis for *V**, one can show that this gives the same definition of the trace as given above.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Given a vector space V over the field F, there is a natural bilinear map *V* × *V*∗ → *F* given by sending (*v*, φ) to the scalar φ(*v*).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The universal property of the tensor product *V* ⊗ *V*∗ automatically implies that this bilinear map is induced by a linear functional on *V* ⊗ *V*∗.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Similarly, there is a natural bilinear map *V* × *V*∗ → Hom(*V*, *V*) given by sending (*v*, φ) to the linear map *w* ↦ φ(*w*)*v*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The universal property of the tensor product, just as used previously, says that this bilinear map is induced by a linear map *V* ⊗ *V*∗ → Hom(*V*, *V*).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] If V is finite-dimensional, then this linear map is a linear isomorphism.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] This fundamental fact is a straightforward consequence of the existence of a (finite) basis of V, and can also be phrased as saying that any linear map *V* → *V* can be written as the sum of (finitely many) rank-one linear maps.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Composing the inverse of the isomorphism with the linear functional obtained above results in a linear functional on Hom(*V*, *V*).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] This linear functional is exactly the same as the trace, providing a definition in coordinate-free terms.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Using the definition of trace as the sum of diagonal elements, the matrix formula tr(**AB**) = tr(**BA**) is straightforward to prove, and was given above.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] In the present perspective, one is considering linear maps S and T, and viewing them as sums of rank-one maps, so that there are linear functionals *φ**i* and *ψ**j* and nonzero vectors *v**i* and *w**j* such that *S*(*u*) = Σ*φ**i*(*u*)*v**i* and *T*(*u*) = Σ*ψ**j*(*u*)*w**j* for any *u* in *V*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Following the same procedure with S and T reversed, one finds exactly the same formula, proving that tr(*S* ∘ *T*) equals tr(*T* ∘ *S*).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The above proof can be regarded as being based upon tensor products, given that the fundamental identity of End(*V*) with *V* ⊗ *V*∗ is equivalent to the expressibility of any linear map as the sum of rank-one linear maps.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] As such, the proof may be written in the notation of tensor products.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Further composition with the trace map then results in *φ*(*w*)*ψ*(*v*), and this is unchanged if one were to have started with (*w*, *ψ*, *v*, *φ*) instead.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] One may also consider the bilinear map End(*V*) × End(*V*) → End(*V*) given by sending (*f*, *g*) to the composition *f* ∘ *g*, which is then induced by a linear map End(*V*) ⊗ End(*V*) → End(*V*).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] It can be seen that this coincides with the linear map *V* ⊗ *V*∗ ⊗ *V* ⊗ *V*∗ → *V* ⊗ *V*∗.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The established symmetry upon composition with the trace map then establishes the equality of the two traces.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] For any finite dimensional vector space V, there is a natural linear map *F* → *V* ⊗ *V*'; in the language of linear maps, it assigns to a scalar c the linear map *c*⋅id*V*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Sometimes this is called *coevaluation map*, and the trace *V* ⊗ *V*' → *F* is called *evaluation map*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] These structures can be axiomatized to define categorical traces in the abstract setting of category theory.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] In particular, traces can be defined for endomorphisms of a finitely generated projective module over a ring, see Tensor product of modules § Trace.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] For a proof expand the expectation directly.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Usually, the random vector is sampled from $\operatorname {N} (\mathbf {0} ,\mathbf {I} )$ (normal distribution) or $\{\pm n^{-1/2}\}^{n}$ (Rademacher distribution).
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] More sophisticated stochastic estimators of trace have been developed.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] If a 2 x 2 real matrix has zero trace, its square is a diagonal matrix.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace of a 2 × 2 complex matrix is used to classify Möbius transformations.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] First, the matrix is normalized to make its determinant equal to one.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Then, if the square of the trace is 4, the corresponding transformation is *parabolic*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] If the square is in the interval [0,4), it is *elliptic*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Finally, if the square is greater than 4, the transformation is *loxodromic*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] See classification of Möbius transformations.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace is used to define characters of group representations.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace also plays a central role in the distribution of quadratic forms.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The trace can be used to classify von Neumann Algebra factors.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Generalizations of the trace can be used to define noncommutative integration theory.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The kernel of this map consists of matrices whose trace is zero, often called **traceless** or **trace free**, and these matrices form the simple Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {sl}}_{n}$ , which is the Lie algebra of the special linear group of matrices with determinant 1.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The special linear group consists of the matrices which do not change volume, while the special linear Lie algebra is the matrices which do not alter volume of *infinitesimal* sets.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] In fact, there is an internal direct sum decomposition ${\mathfrak {gl}}_{n}={\mathfrak {sl}}_{n}\oplus K$ of operators/matrices into traceless operators/matrices and scalar operators/matrices.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Formally, one can compose the trace (the counit map) with the unit map $K\to {\mathfrak {gl}}_{n}$ of "inclusion of scalars" to obtain a map ${\mathfrak {gl}}_{n}\to {\mathfrak {gl}}_{n}$ mapping onto scalars, and multiplying by *n*.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Dividing by *n* makes this a projection, yielding the formula above.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] $B(\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )$ is called the Killing form; it is used to classify Lie algebras.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] For a complex simple Lie algebra (such as ${\mathfrak {sl}}$ *n*), every such bilinear form is proportional to each other; in particular, to the Killing form.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] There is a generalization to a general representation $(\rho ,{\mathfrak {g}},V)$ of a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , such that $\rho$ is a homomorphism of Lie algebras $\rho :{\mathfrak {g}}\rightarrow {\text{End}}(V).$ The trace form ${\text{tr}}_{V}$ on ${\text{End}}(V)$ is defined as above.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The bilinear form $\phi (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )={\text{tr}}_{V}(\rho (\mathbf {X} )\rho (\mathbf {Y} ))$ is symmetric and invariant due to cyclicity.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The concept of trace of a matrix is generalized to the trace class of compact operators on Hilbert spaces, and the analog of the Frobenius norm is called the Hilbert–Schmidt norm.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] If *K* is a trace-class operator, then for any orthonormal basis $\{e_{n}\}_{n=1}$ , the trace is given by $\operatorname {tr} (K)=\sum _{n}\left\langle e_{n},Ke_{n}\right\rangle ,$ and is finite and independent of the orthonormal basis.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] This trace can be generalized to von Neumann Algebras.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The Dixmier trace generalizes the usual trace beyond trace-class operators.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The partial trace is another generalization of the trace that is operator-valued.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] For more properties and a generalization of the partial trace, see traced monoidal categories.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] If A is a general associative algebra over a field k , then a trace on A is often defined to be any functional $\operatorname {tr} :A\to k$ which vanishes on commutators; $\operatorname {tr} ([a,b])=0$ for all $a,b\in A$ .
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Such a trace is not uniquely defined; it can always at least be modified by multiplication by a nonzero scalar.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] A supertrace is the generalization of a trace to the setting of superalgebras.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] The operation of tensor contraction generalizes the trace to arbitrary tensors.
[src:tensor-networks/trace-linear-algebra] Gomme and Klein (2011) define a matrix trace operator $\operatorname {trm}$ that operates on block matrices and use it to compute second-order perturbation solutions to dynamic economic models without the need for tensor notation.
